segments.text: You mentioned poker playing.
Was there a fair amount of poker playing?
Well, you know, I never did gamble myself, but some of the boys did.
Of course, that goes on in every kind of society.
Once in a while, they'd get caught, and that was it when they got caught.
Well, I asked somebody about working in school, and somebody told me about somebody that he knew
They worked his way through school the last two years with a pair of dice.
Well, that's right.
A lot of them do.
These boys got allowances, you know, and their parents would send them so much allowance every month.
So this allowance would come in.
I knew an old boy from my hometown there.
He got an allowance every month.
His daddy was a banker, and he got a pretty good allowance every month.
Boy, in two or three days, that allowance was gone.
He was a great, he rolled eyes, he'd do anything.
So then I remember one time he got broke and he got the job selling pies.
He was up there in Mitchell Hall selling his pies.
So he went around, you know, and he got into a crap game up there and he lost all his pies.
Who was he selling pies for?
himself, trying to make a little money.
Where'd he get them?
Did he buy them in Bryan or something?
I don't remember where he got those pies.
I don't remember where he got those pies.
Well, he'd buy the whole pie and sell it in slices then.
No, he'd just sell the pie.
And another thing they used to do was, I never knew what apricot pie tasted like until I got to be a sophomore.
So that was the favorite cushion, we called cushions.
as a favorite cook, apricot pie.
So we got maybe apricot pie maybe once or twice a week.
So they'd come in, we'd have apricot pie, and the chef would say, all right, fish, bring that pie down here.
So he'd tell some fish, he said, now, I want you to get this pie out of the mess hall and bring it up to my room.
So I caught some old fellow, some old boy up there one time.
He had about 25 or 30 pies in his trunk.
He'd store them away in his trunk.
So we'd have our job then would be
Smuggle this pie, put it in your blouse, you know, and smuggle it out of the mess hall.
Of course, there's an old Army sergeant.
He was an old Sergeant Foster.
I remember that.
He'd just straight in there, you know, and he'd be there at the mess hall door.
He'd see something, notice something, and he'd come here.
Come here.
He'd just reach in and unbutton his reach and take that pie.
Yeah, you mean you put the whole pie in your bluff.
Sure, sure.
They'd just take it up to the room.
Then at night, when you see this upperclassman, he'd invite a few of his friends in.
They'd have a snack, a pie snack.
I never knew what apricot pie tasted like until I got to see it.
But they had it all the time you were there as a freshman, but you never got it.
Then you used to have what's called a prune race.
They gave us a lot of prunes, I guess, to keep us kind of regulated, you know, physically.
Nobody seemed to care much for prunes, but I happened to like prunes.
I always have liked prunes.
So they'd come in, usually Saturday night we'd get prunes.
They'd come in, you know, and they'd say, well, nobody eats prunes tonight.
So we're going to have a prune race.
So...
the upperclassman down at this end of the table, he'd pick out a freshman, his freshman, and the other guy, he'd pick out his freshman.
And when the meal was finished, nobody leaves the table now.
When the meal was finished, well, then they'd give each one of us a bowl of prunes and give us a toothpick.
And whichever one got the prunes finished first, he won.
Well, if you
If you won for your upperclassman, then the other upperclassman, he'd work you over.
And then if you lost by the one you lost for, he'd work you over.
So you couldn't win either way.
What was the toothpick for, picking up the prunes?
Yeah, you'd pick up prunes with a toothpick and stick them in your mouth, and the one cleaned up his dish.
Well, a big bowl of prunes, enough for 12 men, you know, two bowls, enough for six men to eat.
You ate the whole bowl.
We'd have to eat it, yeah.
I meant you were regular for a couple days.
Another thing that happened funny, I was walking post over one night.
See, we had the artillery down there, and we had the horse cavalry, and we had the Sigma Corps, and we had the Air Corps.
So the old Foster Hall used to quarter the battery.
The battery was quartered in Foster Hall.
So I was in the infantry.
I was nothing to them.
So they'd send a boy from the infantry, a blue catcord on the cat, or some other organization, some other company, you know, into this Foster Hall.
Those artillery boys give you a hard time.
But you know how old Foster Hall, you ever seen Foster Hall?
Only pictures.
Well, it's built in two wings, and you had a rotunda.
up four floors, four floors up.
They had a rotunda, and each round, each one of these, they had banister ratings, and it didn't clear up the top of the ceiling.
So you had to walk from one wing to the other.
So I was over there one night walking post in Foster Hall, and the thing was that when the Sentinel walked
come in the open, you see, for those boys up there in the battery, they'd get a big GI can full of water and get up on the top floor.
And when you went, they'd come in the open there, they'd let you have that can, that GI can full of water.
So I was over there one night walking post, and I was pretty careful.
I was always looking when I went by.
We had an old commandant down there we called Bull Muller.
Old Bull.
Oh, he just scared to death.
He had those steely blue eyes, you know.
The story was he'd been over a bunch of niggers all his life.
And he was rough.
I don't mean anything.
He was rough.
And he just scared these freshmen to death, you know.
He'd just take that rifle and swing it up there and look at it.
And I had to always pardon him.
Went with him and he'd look at it, you know, and he'd just nod to that sergeant.
And that meant you got around to it.
So you'd take in a number, your name, and your company, and so forth.
So he came in there and it was raining that night and he had on one of these old ponchos like this.
like these old officers used to wear.
So he came up, and I came to present arms.
He says, put your fourth general order, Senator.
I stopped just outside of that rotunda.
See, an old bull, he was a little outside of me.
So I started spitting that general order out.
And boy, the first thing I heard was, shh, here comes that water.
And it missed me, but it just hit old Bull full blast.
He shook that old poncho, and he had one of these old campaign hats, you know, with an officer's hat card on it.
He shook his poncho, and he looked up, you know, I just wet him all over.
He looked up, went up, he whirled around, he started up the stairs, and he got about halfway.
And I guess he figured, oh, he knew then he couldn't find out who it was.
He didn't have a chance.
So then the next day, the colonel got up and read a general order in the mess hall.
The entire battery was campus for a month.
Everybody in the foster halls was campus for a month.
We used to have a lot of fun.
Oh, yeah, that hell of a lot.
Then another kid down there, he was a country boy, you know, and he was very ambitious.
We used to... A fella get too ambitious, you know, we'd give him a hard time.
That is, we'd play lots of tricks on him.
They used to have these old bellhop uniforms.
We called them, you know, days gone by with these big insignia on them.
So we got...
a hold of this old boy.
His name, I believe his name was Green, I forget now.
But anyway, they got a hold of this old boy and they told him, he says, you know, Green, you're doing line in this military and the first thing you know, you're going to be a corporal.
So, of course, that went over big with him.
So then they got one of these old bellhop uniforms and
And he sewed one of these big chevrons, you know, like they used to wear it, covered carpal chevrons on his sleeve here.
And I told him, and I says, we got some upperclassmen in on it too, see.
And we told him, and I said, Green, you're going to be color carpal.
There's no such thing as a color carpal.
You're going to be color carpal here.
for this regiment.
And he says, but there's one stipulation.
He says, you're going to have to earn this color corporal.
You're going to have to get out and do guard duty on the main drag, I mean, on the military walk every Sunday afternoon.
And he says, your duty is going to be to stop every car that comes along and search the car for liquor.
There's liquor coming on this campus.
You know what that means, liquor on the campus.
So he fell for it.
We used to have these ministers, various ministers that come down every Sunday, you know, to preach various denominations.
So they had an Episcopalian, I think he's a right reverend or something.
And so old Prexy, that was old Dr. Brazell, he was out on a Sunday afternoon showing him around the campus, you know.
So here this old boy, he was out there with his gun, you know, around the flagpole and
Walking around, he stopped the car and coming up to old Prexy's car.
Of course, old Prexy had a shopper.
So he told him, he said he wanted to inspect the car for liquor.
He had orders to inspect the car for liquor.
So old Prexy, he wanted to know what that meant.
So he finally told him, he says, you've been duped, son, so you're going back to your room.
And of course, it embarrassed him around this preacher.
But he sent the old boy home back, and it finally soaked in what the deal was.
We had a lot of fun.
We had more fun than they have now.
We had the junior band.
They don't have that anymore, I guess.
I don't think they do.
It varies from year to year what they do have.
I believe they still have the senior ring dance.
and they have a...
I don't think you call it a senior banquet.
I think the former students have a banquet of some kind for all the graduating seniors, and they try to get them to join the Association of Former Students and things like that.
When I was there, they had three dances.
There was a Thanksgiving hop, the RV hop,
And the final bowl, that's three hops.
And on various Saturday nights, you know, they had the Aggieland Six.
They had a good orchestra.
Who played in the Aggieland Six?
Was that students or faculty?
No, students.
It was made up of students.
You remember this fellow Bartlett?
That was Saul Bartlett that was retired as a four-star general in the Air Corps?
Wasn't it Bartlett?
No, let's see what it was.
He was a junior when I was a senior.
And if I remember it right, I believe he paid the trombone or something.
But he was in that orchestra, the old one.
I don't know whether I may have the name wrong.
But anyway, he wound up a four-star general in the Air Corps.
They gave him a big review down there sometimes.
Oh, and I see that he was down there some time ago.
I wouldn't be as sure about that.
Did you have any favorite instructors?
Well, we had a lot of unfavorites.
Well, but...
What kind did you have as unfavorites?
Well, I guess they used to say the fourth year of fish chemistry was always the hardest.
That's a fact.
You'd see seniors with leather putts on, boots, going over there and taking that first year of chemistry.
You want a real story?
Yeah.
A little life to it?
Sure.
You don't mind the words, the language?
No, no.
Well, we had a function down there that we used to call, we used to call the Piss Mount.
And that was, that started on the first day of December and lasted until we went home for Christmas.
So, uh,
They'd hang a number on a fella's door.
That was just a freshman.
They'd hang a number on a fella's door.
And he used to be the...
In other words, he was the rain for this Pismount that night.
So it was held between Tattoo and Taps.
So I remember I saw a light.
He was from my hometown.
And they hung it on old Saul Wright's door.
Then that happened in Milner Hall, too, when I was a fisherman.
So old Saul, he said, well, he said, everybody's coming out now in sidearms, stripped naked, very naked, stark naked, in sidearms, and dressed caps.
And he says, shoes, russet shoes.
And that's all we had on.
So we'd form out there, and then they had what they called the flaming fist pot bearer, which was an old chamber pot with some kerosene in it or something.
And they'd rag and they'd light this, and then they had an escort for the
and they'd march down before we lined up in formation.
They'd march down this line, you see, formation.
And then the master of ceremonies, that's what I was trying to think about.
Old Saul, he was the master of ceremonies.
This old prof we had down there, they called him Squirrel Tooth Moore.
He had buck teeth, and his teeth had always shone, and we called him Squirrel Tooth Moore.
His name was Moore.
So, old Saul, he was a master of ceremony, so old Saul, that night, he got down and delivered a prayer up to

Santa Claus says, when you come with your bag, he says, oh, Santa Claus, when you come with your bag, he says, for God's sakes, pick up old Square Tooth Moore and take him out here and dump him in the fish tank.

so old Prexy had got wind of it some way I don't know and he and old Sergeant Smart he was a very straight military sort of a guy you know had snow white hair and always wore a black suit and a black bow tie and a white shirt and old Prexy did the same thing he had a black suit always a black suit black hat and a bow tie black bow tie and so they just happened to
Somebody put them wise, you know.
So they just happened to be coming up the top of the flight.
This thing was up on the third floor.
And they just happened to be getting up there to the top floor about the time old Saul was asking Santa Claus to drop old squirrel two more in the fish tank.
So old Prexy, he just tapped him on the back.
And I was pretty close by.
He just tapped him on the back, and he says, get up from there, young man.
And old Thaw looked down, and he saw those black shoes, you know.
And he just come up kind of slow.
And old Praxey kind of grabbed him and shook him a little.
And he says, young man, he says, you know what you've been doing?
And he said, old Thaw, he stammered out yesterday.
He turned around to old Sergeant Smart, and he says, Sergeant, he says, this is the most sacrilegious.
He looked at us all, you know, naked.
He says, this is the most sacrilegious thing I've ever witnessed.
I didn't know such things could happen in this school.
And he says, who's responsible for this?
The old sergeant, he didn't know anything.
So he says, all of you get to your rooms.
So we skedaddled.
Boy, we couldn't get there fast enough.
And Pinky Hudson, he was the company commander.
He roomed down in the corner room for me.
So old Pecksey, he turned around, he charged down there and opened the door.
He didn't even stop to knock.
He says, Captain Hudson, do you know what's been going on out here?
And old Pinky, he kind of stammered around.
Of course he knew, but he didn't say anything.
He said, I'm a good man to jerk those three buttons off your shirt right now at this instance.
He said, you report to me tomorrow.
So he left.
But that was the funniest thing, you know.
We had a big laugh on that.
That was the funniest thing.
We had lots of fun.
That's the old days, boy.
That's what went on down there.
Did you ever get any stories like this?
No, but that was a nightly occurrence then from the 1st of December.
From the 1st of December until, I don't know, maybe I shouldn't be talking this.
Hell, they might want to kick me out of the college.
Oh, I doubt that.
But those things, you know, are stamped on my memory of those days.
And the junior banquets, you know, we had that junior banquets
We had lots of fun then.
I noticed in looking at the Longhorn for your senior year that you were in the Saddle and Sirloin Club.
And that's what, a club for animal husbandry majors?
Yeah.
It was anybody, agricultural students, you see.
I went down there and I signed up for civil engineering.
That's what my dad sent me down there.
So I attended classes for a while.
About two weeks, I think it was.
And I saw that I'd never be an engineer.
I'm not good enough in math.
I never did good enough.
So I switched over to agriculture.
I saw if I wanted to stay there.
So I switched over to agriculture.
And I was interested in that more than I was anything.
I always liked it.
I liked farming.
I liked farming and I liked ranch life and like that.
So I finished as an A.H.,
And they didn't have all this stuff they have now.
We had animal husbandry.
We had dairy husbandry.
We had horticulture.
And that was about it.
And then agricultural education.
Were there several organizations that the students could belong to?
I know that you belong to the Saddle and Sirloin Club.
Were there other kind of clubs that you belonged to other than hometown clubs?
Well, we had our hometown clubs, yeah.
We had our hometown clubs, Houston clubs, and Dallas clubs, and so forth.
But otherwise, there wasn't much.
Any kind of social organizations?
Well, they had the masons.
And some of the boys down there belonged to the masons and all.
The social life, I guess you would think now, is rather limited on that.
It's just kind of a filly.
What we kind of made our own social life.
We got along pretty good.
Go back to the instructors.
You indicated that the chemistry department was kind of about the least favorite of all, I guess.
Well...
I don't know.
I passed the freshman chemistry in flying colors.
I met my Waterloo in the organic chemistry, and I had to take that over twice.
But it seemed that the freshman chemistry, more freshmen failed in freshman chemistry than any other one thing.
I don't know why it was.
But the old squirrel tooth, he was a good instructor.
He wasn't anything like it.
We just...
We had a nickname, you know, for nearly all those, like old Script Mitchell, we called him Script Mitchell.
We had another old instructor down there we called Beowulf.
He was always talking about Beowulf.
He must have been in the English department then.
He was in the English department, yeah.
Had a big bunch of fuzzy hair standing all up, you know.
Some of them were characters, those old props.
I believe some of them still are.
Yeah.
I thought they'd teach you school that way.
He gets kind of... Well, I guess he gets away from everything, the boys, and it kind of makes him...
He's kind of odd in some respects, yeah.
You mentioned in talking about this piss mouth that the president came in, went to the company commander's door and threatened to...
rip off his three buttons that night, which brings up an interesting point.
Did both the president and the commandant have the authority to downgrade a student in the military?
Oh, yeah.
In other words, either one of them could have done it.
Sure, anybody could have done it.
Oh, I got busted.
They made me color sergeant down there, and I got busted.
Color sergeant.
And then the old Major Morris busted me.
And the reason I got busted was that I was going out for wrestling, and then I was going out for football, and I got one of these ambitious boys in my company to sub for me, see.
And so the thing dragged on for a while, and
I didn't, uh, I wasn't too eager to change over anyway.
I didn't care.
I didn't care too much about it.
And, uh, old Major Morris called me up when I found a red slip in my mailbox to report to the commandant.
So I went over there and old Major Morris, he says, I don't think it's fair that you wear the chevron and the other boy carry the flag, do you?
I said, no, I don't believe it is.
So I got reduced back to sergeant.
What was the general attitude of the students towards Prexy Bazell and to the commandant?
Did they like him?
Did they like him or did they dislike him?
Well, Prexy, Dr. Bazell made a fine.
He was a fine college president.
He did a lot for that school.
He was a fine college president.
We all liked Prexy.
Yeah, we liked him.
We got along with him all right.
I remember I was going down the sidewalk one day, and I met Prexy.
And I says, how do you do, Dr. Goodell?
So he went on by and stopped me and says,
He called me and said, Freshman.
He knew I was a freshman.
He says, Freshman.
I stopped.
He said, Come here.
He says, Don't you know how to speak to me?
I said, Well, sir, I just stammered.
I couldn't say anything too scary.
He says,
From now on, when you meet me, he says, I'm the president of A&M.
I'm the president of the college.
He says, when you meet me, you salute me, like you do in Oxford.
I said, yes, sir.
We all saluted Brexit when we met him.
I didn't know that.
I hadn't been there long.
I didn't know that.
I'm interested to hear that, because I would not have thought that you would salute anybody other than a military officer.
Oh, yeah, we saluted Brexit.
I suppose you'd salute the president of the United States, wouldn't you?
Well, he, in effect, is the commander-in-chief of the military.
Well, he's out of uniform.
Well, Prexy, he was the commander-in-chief, in effect, of the college.
See, everything, anything, when a fellow got canned, well, it had to go through Prexy.
He was the one that put the final lash on the tree.
But as far as busting you from military rank, the commandant could do that on his own, or the president could do it on his own.
Well, they wouldn't have busted the senior, because that was out of the question to have busted the senior.
I don't know what they'd done to him, but that old Prexy, he was in a kind of a rage then, you know.
working under impulse.
He was so put out with this thing that had been going on, he just thought it was terrible, see, just terrible.
He just never had, he couldn't imagine, he says, Sergeant Smart, I can't imagine that anything like this would go on in an institution of learning.
And you mentioned two different commandants, Morris and Muller, I believe.
Were they both about equal, or did the students like one better than the other?
Well, now Morris wasn't exactly the commandant.
I think Ike Ashburn was the commandant at that time.
But Morris was the head of the military.
He was a major in the military.
He had charge of the military end of it, see.
In other words, he was a ranking officer, and they had several officers down there, one down to captain, one down to lieutenant.
But he was ranking, so he had the...
In other words, he was the commandant.
He had charge of the commandant, the military part of it.
He had the right to bust you just like that.
That's right.
I remember somebody else had told me that somebody got the idea that it'd be good to have a civilian commandant.
And that's when they made Ashburn, gave him the title of commandant.
Yeah, he was commandant.
And then I believe at one time he was also dean of men, I think.
But heretofore, they'd always had a military...
Old Bull Muller was a colonel.
He was a full colonel.
And he was a commandant there before Ike Ashburn.
